text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!EndangeredLanguages]]%0a%0a!Macanese%0a%0a:Author: vincent_c%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThe creole language of Macau%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aMacanese is a language that Ethnologue labels as endangered (I can't access the EGIDS level). The language is sometimes also called Patuá, and originated from a creole in Malacca, and was brought to Macau through Portuguese colonizers. The language never took root as an official language, and was confined to use in private as it was stigmatized and seen as a "broken Portuguese". Additionally, the population that spoke Macanese was always small, as it was confined to the small region of Macau. With Macau's return to China in 1999, the population is now dominantly Han Chinese and the Macanese language is a minority that can only rely on being passed down through generations. The view on the language has shifted in recent years, as locals have become more proud of their heritage and groups such as the Macanese Association and Doci Papiaçam di Macau have made efforts to preserve the language such as in the form of plays performed in Macanese. %0a%0aSource: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/10/macau-city-losing-language-china-portuguese-macanese%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210506-152844-607890#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Patua Speakers and Music %0a-> - saumyaB%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aBelow is a link to a video of two Patua speakers talking about their language and a link to a music video of a song written by a Patua poet named José “Ade” dos Santos Ferreira. In the first video, Aida de Jesus, a 103-year old Patua speaker, and her daughter Sonia discuss Macanese culture and the food they serve at their Macanese-style restaurant. They go on to talk about how fewer and fewer generations are learning Patua, and many people in Macau these days don’t know a lot about Patua - even Patua speakers are sometimes mistaken to be foreigners. Sonia even recalls being told not to speak Patua in school as it wasn’t “real” Portuguese. %0a%0aI thought the second video, which was cited in the first, was very cool. The music in the video is sung in Patua, but the video has subtitles in Cantonese, Portuguese, and English. As the first video pointed out, Patua contains influences from all the countries on the Portugese trade route, like Malaysia, India, and China. The music is very lively and it has the characteristic guitar and timbre of Portuguese music.%0a%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yLxubYfVyRY&ab_channel=Goldthread%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JmPYVbKWF70&ab_channel=MiguelFernandes%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210506-152844-607890#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210508-220148-382550#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-08.05.2021 - 15:01-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210508-220148-382550 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!chester_g%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''Origins'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aWhen did the macanese language first originate in China? I am curious because you mentioned Portuguese colonizers.  %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-220148-382550#%0a#foxbegin 210508-133011-261730#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-08.05.2021 - 06